column10: RUNIC LETTER FEHU FEOH FE F
column13: RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER F — Runes are alphabetical signs in their own right, but in Medieval Nordic manuscripts written in the Latin alphabet they function as abbreviation characters, e.g. the f rune, meaning ‘fé’ (cattle and/or goods). The Unicode descriptive name for this character is RUNIC LETTER FEHU FEOH FE F, but here a simpler name has been given, RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER F.

column10: RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER M
column13: RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER M — In Medieval Nordic manuscripts written in the Latin alphabet, the m rune serves as an abbreviation for ‘maðr’ (man). The Unicode descriptive name for this character is RUNIC LETTER LONG-BRANCH-MADR M, but here a simpler name has been given, RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER M.
The zero width joiner can be used to indicate a visual/sporadic ligature (between the two or more letters) which can then be converted to a single glyph using font technologies.

column13: The distinction between the two characters above are not fully taken care of by using the COMBINING ACUTE ACCENT. The first of the two characters has the accent positioned centrally above, while the second has it firmly above the first part of the ligature. This difference is reflected in the character en- tities and the differnt codepoints.

column13: The position of the two diacritcal marks is not fully taken care of by the decomposed encoding, using the COMBINING ACUTE (0301) and COMBINING MACRON (0304). The acute is located above the first part of the ligature, while the macron is located above the second part; they are not positioned on top of each other, like in the other glyphs in this subrange. This is reflected in the character entity, which is ávmacrlig; and not æmacracute;.
